('business:6-3-globalisation:match:54b5b7f4', 'business', 'business:6-3-globalisation', '6.3 Globalisation', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Unit Cost”?", "options": ["When an MNC sends profits earned in a host country back to its home country headquarters.", "The process by which business activity around the world has become increasingly interconnected.", "The cost of producing one unit — lower when productivity is higher.", "A tax on a good or service that is imported into a country."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "“Unit Cost” means: The cost of producing one unit — lower when productivity is higher."}'::jsonb),
('business:6-3-globalisation:match:7a631873', 'business', 'business:6-3-globalisation', '6.3 Globalisation', 'match', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Which definition matches the key term “Profit Repatriation”?", "options": ["The process by which business activity around the world has become increasingly interconnected.", "A tax on a good or service that is imported into a country.", "A limit on the amount or value of a good that can be imported.", "When an MNC sends profits earned in a host country back to its home country headquarters."]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "“Profit Repatriation” means: When an MNC sends profits earned in a host country back to its home country headquarters."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:exam:6eab2ff9', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q1", "question": "This data helps the company understand its business performance because it shows that: [1 mark]", "options": ["Both advertising campaigns were cost effective", "Campaign A was cost effective, but campaign B was not", "Campaign B was cost effective, but campaign A was not", "Neither of the advertising campaigns were cost effective"], "caseStudy": "A well-known restaurant chain is reviewing its business performance. Financial data about two of its recent advertising campaigns are shown below.\n\n• Campaign A: Weekly cost of running the campaign = £3 million. Average weekly sales BEFORE = £4 million. DURING = £6 million. AFTER = £4 million.\n\n• Campaign B: Weekly cost of running the campaign = £0.6 million. Average weekly sales BEFORE = £4 million. DURING = £5 million. AFTER = £5 million.", "hint": "Think about what ''cost effective'' means — does the campaign generate more in lasting sales than it costs to run?", "starter": "The correct answer is C because..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — Campaign B was cost effective, but campaign A was not [1 mark]</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> Campaign B costs £0.6m per week and raised weekly sales from £4m to £5m — a £1m increase that was <strong>sustained</strong> after the campaign ended. The permanent sales gain exceeds the cost. Campaign A raised sales by £2m during the campaign, but sales returned to £4m afterwards — meaning the £3m weekly cost produced no lasting benefit, making it not cost effective.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A</strong> is wrong because Campaign A did NOT produce a lasting increase in sales — therefore it was not cost effective.</li><li><strong>B</strong> is wrong — it is the opposite of the correct answer.</li><li><strong>D</strong> is wrong because Campaign B clearly WAS cost effective given its sustained sales increase.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:exam:86d207fb', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q5", "question": "The impact of risk taken by a business: [1 mark]", "options": ["Affects all business functions", "Affects all business stakeholders equally", "Only affects the finance function", "Only affects the owners of the business"], "hint": "Think about what happens to a business when a risky decision is made — does it affect just one department or all of them?", "starter": "The correct answer is A because..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: A — Affects all business functions [1 mark]</h5><p><strong>Why A is correct:</strong> Risk is inherently cross-functional. A risky business decision — for example, launching a new product or opening a new branch — simultaneously affects operations (must produce more), HR (must recruit more), marketing (must promote the new launch) and finance (must fund it all). Risk does not fall on just one function.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>B</strong> is wrong because risk does NOT affect all stakeholders equally — shareholders carry the financial risk of investment loss, while employees carry the risk of job security. The impacts are different in nature and magnitude.</li><li><strong>C</strong> is wrong because risk extends well beyond the finance function — it affects production capacity, staffing levels and marketing strategies.</li><li><strong>D</strong> is wrong because while owners/shareholders bear significant financial risk, employees, suppliers and customers are also affected by the business''s risk decisions.</li></ul></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:exam:68174ae2', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'exam', 'mcq', 1, '{"num": "Q6", "question": "The marketing function of a well-known action toy manufacturer is about to launch a major advertising campaign. This advertising campaign will affect the operations function of the business because: [1 mark]", "options": ["Job production will need to be used to speed up production", "Market research into which toy figures are most popular will be required", "More sets of action toy figures will need to be produced", "Vacancies for action toy designers will need to be advertised"], "hint": "The operations function is about PRODUCTION. What will happen to production if the advertising campaign successfully drives up demand?", "starter": "The correct answer is C because..."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Answer: C — More sets of action toy figures will need to be produced [1 mark]</h5><p><strong>Why C is correct:</strong> A successful advertising campaign will increase consumer demand for the toys. The operations function must respond by increasing production output to ensure there is enough stock to meet this higher demand. This is a direct example of a marketing decision creating an interdependency with the operations function.</p><p><strong>Why the other options are wrong:</strong></p><ul><li><strong>A</strong> is wrong because job production is slow and individually customised — it would reduce output speed, not increase it. Mass production methods would be needed to meet higher demand.</li><li><strong>B</strong> is wrong because market research is a marketing function activity, not an operations function activity.</li><li><strong>D</strong> is wrong because advertising vacancies for toy designers is an HR function activity, not operations.</li></ul><p><strong>Examiner''s Comment:</strong> Although the question mentions advertising (a marketing activity), the focus is on the impact on OPERATIONS. Some candidates answered B because they saw ''market research'' but this is still a marketing activity, not operations.</p></div>", "modelAnswer": ""}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:43460fba', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A well-known restaurant chain is reviewing its business performance. Campaign A costs £3m/week and raised sales from £4m to £6m but they dropped back to £4m after. Campaign B costs £0.6m/week and raised sales from £4m to £5m and stayed at £5m after. This data shows that:", "options": ["Both advertising campaigns were cost effective", "Campaign A was cost effective, but campaign B was not", "Campaign B was cost effective, but campaign A was not", "Neither of the advertising campaigns were cost effective"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: C. Campaign B is cost effective because the £1m increase in weekly sales (from £4m to £5m) has been sustained after the campaign, meaning the £0.6m weekly cost generates a net gain. Campaign A boosted sales by £2m during the campaign, but sales returned to £4m afterwards — meaning the £3m weekly cost produced no lasting benefit."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:cedcb699', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A manufacturer has decided to run a marketing campaign on national television in a month''s time. As a result of this decision, which one of the following actions might also be necessary?", "options": ["Finance should stop monitoring cash flow", "Human resources should employ some temporary production workers", "Operations management should reduce output", "Purchasing should buy smaller quantities of raw materials"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: B. If the marketing campaign is successful, demand for the product will increase. The business will need to increase production to meet this higher demand, which means HR will need to employ additional temporary production workers. Options A, C and D are all the opposite of what would be needed."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:8efac32e', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The marketing function of a well-known action toy manufacturer is about to launch a major advertising campaign. This advertising campaign will affect the operations function of the business because:", "options": ["Job production will need to be used to speed up production", "Market research into which toy figures are most popular will be required", "More sets of action toy figures will need to be produced", "Vacancies for action toy designers will need to be advertised"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: C. The advertising campaign (a marketing decision) will increase demand for the toys. Operations must respond by increasing production output to meet this new demand. Option A is wrong because job production is slow, not fast. Option B is a marketing activity, not operations. Option D relates to HR."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:2a8ed09b', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The interdependent nature of business activity means that:", "options": ["Businesses need to merge to increase market share", "Entrepreneurs should favour high risk options", "Global trade is increasing", "The functional areas in a business are linked"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Correct answer: D. Interdependence means that the functional areas of a business (finance, marketing, operations and HR) are all linked and connected to one another. A decision in one area will always have an effect on at least one other area."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:0f77d827', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The impact of risk taken by a business:", "options": ["Affects all business functions", "Affects all business stakeholders equally", "Only affects the finance function", "Only affects the owners of the business"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "Correct answer: A. Risk taken by a business can affect all business functions. For example, a risky decision to launch a new product involves operations (producing it), marketing (promoting it), HR (staffing it) and finance (funding it). Risk does not affect all stakeholders equally, nor is it limited to the finance function or owners alone."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:3ec6980b', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Finance performance data for Pico Ltd:<table class=\"case-table\"><caption>Pico Ltd — Financial Performance</caption><tr><th>Year</th><th>Revenue</th><th>Costs</th></tr><tr><td>2017</td><td>£3.1m</td><td>£2.9m</td></tr><tr><td>2018</td><td>£3.3m</td><td>£2.9m</td></tr><tr><td>2019</td><td>£3.5m</td><td>£2.9m</td></tr></table>According to the table, which of the following MUST be true?", "options": ["Pico Ltd has improved its market share", "Pico Ltd has decreased its prices year on year", "Pico Ltd has made a profit in all three years", "Pico Ltd has not paid its variable costs"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: C. In all three years, revenue exceeds costs (e.g. £3.1m > £2.9m in 2017), meaning Pico Ltd has made a profit in every year. Option A cannot be confirmed without knowing total market size. Option B is not necessarily true — revenue could have increased due to selling more units at the same price. Option D is incorrect as costs are recorded."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:5f63923b', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Following recent financial success, a business has decided to double the size of its workforce. This decision will significantly increase the workload of the:", "options": ["Finance function because new recruits need to be trained", "Human resources function because applicants need to be interviewed", "Marketing function because person specifications need to be produced", "Purchasing function because contracts of employment need to be issued"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: B. Doubling the workforce means a large-scale recruitment drive. The HR function is responsible for advertising vacancies, shortlisting applications, and interviewing candidates. Training is also an HR function (not finance). Person specifications and contracts of employment are also HR tasks, not marketing or purchasing."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:e73c85c1', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Last year''s financial performance data:<table class=\"case-table\"><caption>Company Performance</caption><tr><th>Company</th><th>Profit / Loss</th></tr><tr><td>Company A</td><td>£22,000</td></tr><tr><td>Company B</td><td>–£6,000</td></tr><tr><td>Company C</td><td>£14,000</td></tr><tr><td>Company D</td><td>–£3,000</td></tr></table>Which company made the greatest loss?", "options": ["Company A", "Company B", "Company C", "Company D"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: B. A negative figure in the profit/loss column means a loss. Company B made a loss of £6,000 and Company D made a loss of £3,000. Since £6,000 is a greater loss than £3,000, Company B made the greatest loss. Companies A and C made profits."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:ec9ff8e7', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "The finance department has forgotten to authorise the purchase of a large order of raw materials. Which of the following is a likely consequence of this?", "options": ["More marketing will be needed", "Production may be delayed", "Sales will increase", "Storage costs will increase"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: B. If raw materials are not purchased because finance failed to authorise the order, the operations function will not have the inputs needed to make products. This demonstrates interdependence — a failure in the finance function directly delays production in the operations function."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:41a949b4', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "A tinned-soup manufacturer is considering extending its product range to include fresh soups. Which one of the following is NOT likely to encourage shareholders to vote for this extension?", "options": ["The opportunity to combine ingredient costs and make higher profits", "The opportunity to gain a reputation for producing healthy meals", "The opportunity to have more customers than other soup manufacturers", "The opportunity to increase the financial risks of the business"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "Correct answer: D. Shareholders invest in a business to receive a financial reward (dividends and share price growth). Increasing financial risk without a clear reward would not attract shareholder support — shareholders generally want risk to be minimised or managed carefully. Options A, B and C all offer potential rewards which would attract shareholders."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:e094a277', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Quarterly revenue data for Padre Stores Ltd in 2020:<table class=\"case-table\"><caption>Padre Stores Ltd — Quarterly Revenue (2020)</caption><tr><th>Store</th><th>Q1 (Jan–Mar)</th><th>Q2 (Apr–Jun)</th><th>Q3 (Jul–Sep)</th><th>Q4 (Oct–Dec)</th></tr><tr><td>Store A</td><td>£42,000</td><td>£48,000</td><td>£52,000</td><td>£60,000</td></tr><tr><td>Store B</td><td>£58,000</td><td>£60,000</td><td>£58,000</td><td>£60,000</td></tr><tr><td>Store C</td><td>£65,000</td><td>£50,000</td><td>£40,000</td><td>£60,000</td></tr></table>The data shows that:", "options": ["Average revenue per store in Q2: Apr–Jun was £39,500", "Store A had an average revenue of £50,500 per quarter", "Store C took more revenue in 2020 than either of the other two stores", "Total revenue in Q1: Jan–Mar was better than in any other quarter"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "Correct answer: B. Store A''s total revenue = £42,000 + £48,000 + £52,000 + £60,000 = £202,000. Average = £202,000 ÷ 4 = £50,500. Option A is wrong (Q2 average = (£48k+£60k+£50k)/3 = £52,667). Option C is wrong (Store C total = £215k; Store B total = £236k). Option D is wrong (Q1 total = £165k; Q4 total = £180k)."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:mcq:eb9c6fe7', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'mcq', 'mcq', 1, '{"question": "Kareem makes hand-made shoes. His performance data is shown below:<table class=\"case-table\"><caption>Kareem''s Shoe Business — Annual Data</caption><tr><th>Year</th><th>Pairs Sold</th><th>Revenue</th><th>Profit / Loss</th></tr><tr><td>Year 1</td><td>104</td><td>£2,080</td><td>–£24,000</td></tr><tr><td>Year 2</td><td>1,040</td><td>£20,800</td><td>£2,000</td></tr><tr><td>Year 3</td><td>820</td><td>£16,400</td><td>–£1,800</td></tr><tr><td>Year 4</td><td>1,860</td><td>£46,500</td><td>£26,000</td></tr></table>According to the data, which of the following is true?", "options": ["Costs have been greater than revenue in all four years", "In Year 2, Kareem reduced the average selling price of the shoes", "In Year 4, Kareem increased the average selling price of the shoes", "Revenue has increased year on year"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "Correct answer: C. Year 3 average price: £16,400 ÷ 820 = £20 per pair. Year 4 average price: £46,500 ÷ 1,860 = £25 per pair. This shows Kareem increased his average price in Year 4. Option A is wrong because revenue exceeded costs in Year 2 and Year 4 (both profitable). Option B is wrong as Year 1 and Year 2 both show a £20 average. Option D is wrong — revenue fell in Year 3."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:1e1e9aec', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The interdependent nature of business means that a decision in one business area will always affect at least one other area."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. This is the core principle of the topic. For example, a marketing decision to increase advertising will affect operations (more production needed), HR (more workers needed) and finance (more money needed). All four areas are linked."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:2d1c591a', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Financial risk only affects the finance department of a business."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. The impact of risk taken by a business affects ALL business functions. A risky decision — such as opening a new branch — affects operations, HR, marketing and finance simultaneously. It does not fall solely on the finance department."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:f5e058d8', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Non-financial rewards for entrepreneurs can include independence and personal satisfaction."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. Not all rewards are monetary. Entrepreneurs value the freedom of being their own boss (independence), the sense of achievement from building something successful, and the impact they have on the lives of customers and employees — these are all non-financial rewards."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:d2e840df', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "The Average Rate of Return (ARR) accounts for the effects of inflation on the value of money."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. This is a key limitation of ARR. It treats money received in the future as having the same value as money today, which ignores inflation. In reality, £10,000 in 10 years is worth less in real terms than £10,000 today."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:3472b39d', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "A business can be profitable and still run out of cash."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. Cash flow and profit are different things. A business might be owed money by customers (debtors) but not yet received it — it is ''profitable on paper'' but has no cash to pay its immediate bills. This is why cash flow management is a separate and critical business activity."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:e90c524f', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "For financial information to be useful, it only needs to be accurate."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. For financial information to be useful it must be: (1) Accurate — so correct decisions can be made; (2) Sufficient — enough data for meaningful comparison; AND (3) Up to date — so it reflects the current market situation. All three qualities are required."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:621346b2', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "In the OCR GCSE examination, the final 9-mark question on Paper 2 always requires a synoptic response linking two areas of business."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. OCR specifies that the final question on Component 02 will always be a synoptic question, requiring candidates to demonstrate understanding of how different business areas are interconnected. Candidates must link a topic from Component 01 with one from Component 02."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:9c8baf84', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Entrepreneurs who carry out market research before launching a product completely eliminate the risk of business failure."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. Market research reduces risk by gathering information about customer needs and market conditions, but it cannot eliminate risk entirely. Consumer preferences can change, competition can intensify unexpectedly, and economic conditions can worsen — all despite thorough research."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:d0a73c2d', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Globalisation can bring both risks and rewards to the shareholders of a business."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": true, "explain": "TRUE. Globalisation brings rewards such as access to larger international markets, higher revenues, more customers and potentially higher dividends. However, it also brings risks such as increased international competition, exposure to exchange rate fluctuations, and the need to manage different legal and cultural environments."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:b9b66ddd', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "When a business doubles its workforce, the marketing function has the biggest increase in workload."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. When a business doubles its workforce, the Human Resources (HR) function has the biggest increase in workload. HR must advertise vacancies, write job descriptions and person specifications, interview candidates, issue contracts of employment, and organise training for new starters."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tf:0d9ff76b', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tf', 'tf', 1, '{"question": "Businesses can only compare their financial performance with their own previous years'' results."}'::jsonb, '{"answer": false, "explain": "FALSE. Businesses can compare their accounts in two ways: year-on-year (against their own previous results) AND against competitors. Comparison with competitors is possible for Limited Companies because they are legally required to publish their accounts, making the data publicly available."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:learn:f012f129', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Key Terms & Official Definitions", "reading": "<p>These are the essential terms you must know for this topic. Learn the <strong>exact wording</strong> — examiners reward precise definitions.</p>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Interdependent Nature of Business:</strong> The links between different areas of business (operations, finance, marketing, HR) that affect decision making, the risks and rewards of business activity, and the use of financial information to aid business decision making.</li>\n          <li><strong>Financial Information:</strong> Includes information about revenues, costs, profit, rates of return, break-even and cash flow — used to help the business make decisions.</li>\n          <li><strong>Business Performance:</strong> A measure of how well a business is doing. Key measures are sales, profits and rates of return.</li>\n          <li><strong>Financial Reward:</strong> The profit made by the business as a return for taking a risk.</li>\n          <li><strong>Financial Risk:</strong> The possibility the business will lose money from decisions it makes. Owners may lose money they invested.</li>\n          <li><strong>Non-Financial Rewards:</strong> To owners, this includes the satisfaction of running a successful business, being in charge, being independent and having an impact on what consumers buy.</li>\n          <li><strong>Non-Financial Risk:</strong> To business owners this includes health risks due to stress and strained relationships with family and friends.</li>\n          <li><strong>Synopticity:</strong> In OCR GCSE Business, this means that knowledge from Component 01 topics is brought together with knowledge from Component 02 topics to answer a question — showing how different areas of business are truly connected.</li>\n          <li><strong>Business Areas:</strong> The four main functional areas of a business: Marketing, Human Resources (HR), Business Operations, and Finance.</li>\n          <li><strong>Globalisation:</strong> The process of interaction and integration between people, companies and governments worldwide — opening up international markets and supply chains.</li>\n        </ul>", "question": "According to the key definitions, what does ''synopticity'' mean in OCR GCSE Business?", "options": ["Bringing together knowledge from Component 01 and Component 02 to answer a question", "The four main functional areas of a business working in isolation", "The possibility that a business will lose money from a decision that it has made", "A measure of how well a business is doing, based on sales and profit"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card defines synopticity as bringing together knowledge from Component 01 and Component 02 topics to show how different business areas are connected."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:learn:a4b144e8', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "The Four Interdependent Business Areas", "reading": "<p>A business has four main functional areas. <strong>Interdependent</strong> means these areas are linked — a decision in one area will always affect at least one other. This is the foundation of the entire topic.</p>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Marketing:</strong> Market research, the marketing mix (price, place, product, promotion), market segmentation, consumer law.</li>\n          <li><strong>Human Resources (HR):</strong> Organisational structure, communication, recruiting and selecting workers, motivating, retaining and training workers, employment law.</li>\n          <li><strong>Business Operations:</strong> Production processes, customer service, location decisions, supply chain management.</li>\n          <li><strong>Finance:</strong> Sources of finance, revenues, costs and profits, break-even analysis, cash flow.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <p>When making decisions, business people must <strong>always</strong> consider the effects of a decision in one area on all other areas. For example:</p>\n        <ul>\n          <li>A <strong>Marketing</strong> decision to launch a new advertising campaign &rarr; <strong>Operations</strong> must increase production to meet higher demand &rarr; <strong>HR</strong> must recruit more workers &rarr; <strong>Finance</strong> must provide the budget and monitor cash flow.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <div class=\"case-study-box\">\n          <h4>Case Study: Wyke Farm</h4>\n          <p>Wyke Farm, a Devon dairy producer, invested in solar panels and biomethane technology. This single decision linked all four areas: <strong>Operations</strong> changed its production process; <strong>Finance</strong> used a £11m bank loan and £2m retained profit; <strong>Marketing</strong> could now promote an environmentally friendly image and sell energy as a new product; <strong>HR</strong> may have needed new skilled workers. The £100,000/month energy saving was a clear financial reward for taking the risk of the investment.</p>\n        </div>", "question": "According to the Wyke Farm case study, which business areas were linked by the solar panel investment?", "options": ["None of the four business areas were affected by the decision", "All four areas — operations, finance, marketing and HR together", "Only the finance department, with no effect on any other area", "Only the marketing department, with no effect on any other area"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card explains Wyke Farm''s solar panel investment linked all four areas: operations changed, finance funded it, marketing promoted it, and HR may have needed new skilled workers."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:learn:dd7777c1', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Risk and Reward in Business", "reading": "<p>Every business decision involves <strong>risk</strong> — the chance that something could go wrong. The motivation for taking that risk is the <strong>reward</strong> — typically profit.</p>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Financial Risk:</strong> Losing the money invested if the business fails or a decision backfires. When owners start a business, they invest their own or borrowed money — if the business is unprofitable, they risk losing it.</li>\n          <li><strong>Non-Financial Risk:</strong> Health problems from stress, long irregular hours, difficulty taking holidays, strained relationships with family and friends due to the pressure of running a business.</li>\n          <li><strong>Lack of Security:</strong> Entrepreneurs often give up previous jobs, losing the security of a regular income.</li>\n          <li><strong>Business Failure:</strong> The biggest risk. If the business cannot generate enough money to survive, it will be forced to close.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <p><strong>Rewards for taking the risk:</strong></p>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Financial Reward:</strong> Profit — the primary driving force behind most business start-ups. Money can be reinvested to help the business grow.</li>\n          <li><strong>Independence:</strong> Being your own boss — having full control over decisions without answering to someone else.</li>\n          <li><strong>Business Success:</strong> This can mean different things: seeing an idea become popular, growing the business, winning awards, building a positive reputation.</li>\n          <li><strong>Non-Financial Reward:</strong> Personal satisfaction, the sense of achievement, being part of the community, making an impact on what consumers buy.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <div class=\"two-col\">\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"col-head\">✓ Rewards of Starting a Business</div>\n            <div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Profit:</strong> The financial return for the entrepreneur''s effort and risk — can be reinvested to grow the business further.</div>\n            <div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Independence:</strong> Full control over decisions, work hours and business direction without reporting to a manager.</div>\n            <div class=\"pro-item\"><strong>Personal Satisfaction:</strong> The non-financial reward of seeing your idea succeed and building something of your own.</div>\n          </div>\n          <div>\n            <div class=\"col-head\">✗ Risks of Starting a Business</div>\n            <div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Financial Loss:</strong> Invested capital (personal savings or loans) could be lost if the business fails to become profitable.</div>\n            <div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Lack of Security:</strong> No guaranteed income, long hours, difficulty taking holidays — a significant personal sacrifice.</div>\n            <div class=\"con-item\"><strong>Business Failure:</strong> The ultimate risk — if revenues cannot cover costs, the business must close, potentially leaving the owner in debt.</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>", "question": "According to this card, what is an example of a non-financial risk to a business owner?", "options": ["Full control over decisions without answering to a manager", "Health problems from stress and strained relationships with family", "The profit made by the business as a return for taking that risk", "Losing the money invested if the business fails or a decision backfires"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card lists health problems from stress and strained family relationships as non-financial risks — distinct from financial risk (losing invested money)."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:learn:5b5d3264', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Minimising Risk", "reading": "<p>Entrepreneurs can take steps to <strong>reduce the risk</strong> of failure before and during the life of a business. These are not guarantees, but they significantly improve the chances of success.</p>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Carry out Market Research:</strong> Gather data on customer needs, competitor prices, and market size before launching. This reduces the risk of producing something nobody wants to buy.</li>\n          <li><strong>Write a Business Plan:</strong> A detailed plan covering objectives, financial forecasts, marketing strategies and operational plans. It forces the entrepreneur to think through every aspect and is required when applying for a bank loan.</li>\n          <li><strong>Ensure Sufficient Finance is Available:</strong> Many businesses fail not because of poor ideas, but because they run out of cash. Planning cash flow carefully and securing enough start-up capital is critical.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <p>All three of these risk-minimisation strategies draw on <strong>financial information</strong> — which demonstrates once again how the different areas of business are interdependent.</p>", "question": "According to this card, what do all three risk-minimisation strategies draw on?", "options": ["Sheer luck, since risk can never actually be reduced by planning", "Legal advice, which is the only way to reduce the risk of failure", "Financial information, showing how business areas are interdependent", "Government grants, which are required before starting any business"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains market research, a business plan, and ensuring sufficient finance all draw on financial information — showing business areas are interdependent."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:learn:b9253656', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Using Financial Information to Make Decisions", "reading": "<p>Businesses use financial information to <strong>measure performance</strong> and <strong>inform decisions</strong>. The most common types include:</p>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Costs and Revenues:</strong> Knowing total costs versus total revenues shows whether the business is profitable.</li>\n          <li><strong>Gross and Net Profit:</strong> Gross profit shows the profit from sales before expenses; net profit shows profit after all costs are deducted.</li>\n          <li><strong>Profit Margins:</strong> Shows what percentage of revenue becomes profit — useful for comparing efficiency over time.</li>\n          <li><strong>Cash Flow:</strong> Shows the timing of money coming in and going out — a business can be profitable but still fail if cash runs out.</li>\n          <li><strong>Break-Even Analysis:</strong> Identifies the sales level at which the business covers all its costs — useful when launching a new product or making investment decisions.</li>\n          <li><strong>Average Rate of Return (ARR):</strong> Used to compare the profitability of different investment options.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <p><strong>For financial information to be useful, it must be:</strong></p>\n        <ul>\n          <li><strong>Accurate:</strong> Incorrect data leads to incorrect decisions and potential financial loss.</li>\n          <li><strong>Sufficient:</strong> There must be enough data to make a meaningful comparison.</li>\n          <li><strong>Up to Date:</strong> Outdated information may be irrelevant, especially if the market has changed significantly.</li>\n        </ul>\n        <div class=\"formula-box\">\n          <strong>Net Profit =</strong> Gross Profit &minus; Expenses (overheads)\n          <br><br>\n            <strong>Gross Profit =</strong> Revenue &minus; Cost of Sales\n            <br><br>\n              <strong>Net Profit Margin (%) =</strong> (Net Profit &divide; Revenue) &times; 100\n            </div>", "question": "According to this card, what does ''net profit margin'' show?", "options": ["What percentage of revenue becomes profit, useful for comparing efficiency", "The total amount of cash a business has in its bank account today", "The total revenue a business receives before any of its costs are deducted", "The exact number of units a business must sell to break even"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains net profit margin shows what percentage of revenue becomes profit, useful for comparing a business''s efficiency over time."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:learn:79132d1e', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Limitations of Financial Information", "reading": "<p>While financial information is essential, it has <strong>limitations</strong> that businesses must be aware of when making decisions.</p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>Inflation:</strong> The Average Rate of Return (ARR) does not account for the effects of inflation on the value of money. £1 today is worth more than £1 in five years'' time — but ARR treats them the same.</li>\n                <li><strong>Historical Data:</strong> Financial accounts are published after the period they cover. A lot may have changed in the market by the time the data is analysed.</li>\n                <li><strong>Incomplete Picture:</strong> Financial data only measures what can be quantified in money. It cannot capture reputation, staff morale, brand loyalty or the external competitive environment.</li>\n                <li><strong>Comparability:</strong> Comparing accounts between businesses can be misleading if they use different accounting methods or operate in different markets.</li>\n              </ul>\n              <p>Businesses typically compare their accounts in two ways:</p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>Year-on-Year:</strong> Comparing this year''s performance against previous years to identify trends.</li>\n                <li><strong>Against Competitors:</strong> Comparing with rivals (only possible for Limited Companies which must publish their accounts) to benchmark performance.</li>\n              </ul>", "question": "According to this card, what limitation does Average Rate of Return (ARR) have?", "options": ["It ignores the cost of the original investment being compared", "It cannot be used to compare two different investment options at all", "It can only ever be calculated by limited companies, not other businesses", "It does not account for the effects of inflation on the value of money"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card explains ARR does not account for inflation — £1 today is worth more than £1 in five years'' time, but ARR treats them the same."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:learn:ff09324b', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'learn', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Synoptic Questions: How to Link Business Areas", "reading": "<p>The final 9-mark question on OCR Paper 2 is <strong>always synoptic</strong> — it requires you to link a topic from Component 01 (e.g. stakeholders, globalisation, environment) with a topic from Component 02 (e.g. cash flow, marketing mix, costs). Here is how to approach these questions:</p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>The Change:</strong> This is the topic that \"makes something happen\" — e.g. a change in marketing, or a decision to go more environmentally friendly. Your Knowledge (K) and Understanding (U) marks come from explaining this topic.</li>\n                <li><strong>The Impact:</strong> This is what is affected — e.g. cash flow, operations, HR. Your Application (APP), Analysis (AN) and Evaluation (EVAL) marks come from explaining the impact on the specific business in the case study.</li>\n              </ul>\n              <div class=\"case-study-box\">\n                <h4>Example: Dog and Gun Inn (Cash Flow)</h4>\n                <p>The question asks: \"Evaluate the impact the <strong>change to marketing</strong> by the Dog and Gun Inn may have had on its <strong>cash flow</strong>.\"</p>\n                <p>&rarr; Knowledge/Understanding marks: define and explain <strong>marketing</strong>.<br>\n                  &rarr; Application/Analysis/Evaluation marks: explain how the specific marketing changes (takeaway menu, website adverts) would have affected the <strong>cash flow</strong> of the Dog and Gun specifically.</p>\n              </div>\n              <p>A common mistake is to write entirely about marketing and forget to link it back to the named impact (cash flow). Always keep asking yourself: <em>\"So what does this mean for the cash flow / costs / revenue of this specific business?\"</em></p>", "question": "According to this card, where do Application, Analysis and Evaluation marks come from in a synoptic question?", "options": ["Describing the ''change'' topic in as much general detail as possible", "Simply repeating the definition of the ''change'' topic several times over again here", "Explaining the impact on the specific business regarding the named ''affected'' topic", "Listing every possible business area without ever linking any of them together"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains APP, AN and EVAL marks come from explaining the impact on the specific business regarding the named ''affected'' topic, such as cash flow."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:10b9d76c', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Students write about ''interdependence'' as simply meaning ''businesses need each other'' or ''companies trade with each other.''</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Interdependence in this context means the four FUNCTIONAL AREAS within a SINGLE business (marketing, HR, operations, finance) are linked. A decision in one internal area affects the others. It is NOT about businesses trading with each other.</p>", "question": "What does ''interdependence'' actually mean in this topic?", "options": ["The four functional areas within a single business are linked to each other", "A business depends on customers trading with each other directly", "A business depends entirely on its own direct competitors in order to succeed", "Different businesses need each other and trade with one another"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains interdependence means the four functional areas within a SINGLE business are linked — it is not about businesses trading with each other."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:aeeb2b62', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> For the 3-mark analyse question, students describe what a function does generally (e.g. ''marketing involves promotion'') without linking it to the specific business in the case study.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The examiner''s report highlighted this was the most common reason for scoring zero. You MUST name a specific marketing activity (Understanding), THEN link it to the specific company named (Application), THEN explain the impact on the other function mentioned in the question (Analysis).</p>", "question": "Why does describing a function generally, e.g. ''marketing involves promotion'', score zero on a 3-mark analyse question?", "options": ["It already contains full application and analysis in one short sentence", "It only applies to finance questions, and never to marketing questions", "It fails to link the activity to the specific business named in the case study", "It is factually incorrect, since marketing never involves promotion at all"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains this was the most common reason for scoring zero — you must name a specific activity, link it to the business, then explain the impact."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:8b57b6bb', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Students confuse ''risk'' with only financial risk — they do not mention non-financial risks like stress, health issues or strained family relationships.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The specification explicitly identifies BOTH financial risk (losing money invested) AND non-financial risk (health, stress, damaged family relationships). For a question asking for two risks, one of each type is a strong answer.</p>", "question": "Does ''risk'' in this topic only refer to financial risk?", "options": ["No — but only because financial risk does not actually exist", "Yes — but only health risks count as a form of financial risk", "No — non-financial risks like stress and strained relationships also count", "Yes — only financial risk is ever recognised in this exam specification"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains the specification identifies BOTH financial risk (losing invested money) AND non-financial risk (health, stress, damaged relationships)."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:b810b613', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Students write that the limitation of ARR is that ''it is hard to calculate'' or ''businesses do not always have the right data.''</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The official, examinable limitation of ARR is that it does NOT account for the effects of INFLATION on the value of money. Money received in the future is worth less in real terms than money received today — ARR ignores this.</p>", "question": "What is the official, examinable limitation of ARR, according to this card?", "options": ["Businesses never have the right data available to calculate it at all", "It can only be used by businesses that have already made a profit", "It does not account for the effects of inflation on the value of money", "It is too difficult for most businesses to actually calculate correctly"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains the official limitation is that ARR ignores inflation — money received in the future is worth less in real terms than money today."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:ba3a5a94', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> For the 9-mark synoptic question, students focus entirely on the ''change'' topic (e.g. marketing) and forget to explain the impact on the ''affected'' topic (e.g. cash flow).</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Your K and U marks come from explaining the ''change'' topic. But your APP, AN and EVAL marks ALL come from explaining the effect on the specific impact named in the question (e.g. cash flow, costs, revenues). You MUST switch focus to the impact in the second half of your answer.</p>", "question": "What mistake do students make when they focus entirely on the ''change'' topic in a 9-mark synoptic question?", "options": ["They forget to explain the impact on the ''affected'' topic named in the question", "They accidentally answer a completely different question by mistake", "They correctly earn every single mark available for the whole question", "They spend too little time explaining what the ''change'' topic actually involves"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains APP, AN and EVAL marks all come from explaining the effect on the named ''affected'' topic — you must switch focus in the second half of the answer."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:84751d1d', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Students confuse ''stakeholders'' with ''shareholders'' — they write an entire answer referring to ''stakeholders'' without ever naming a specific one.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> To gain Application and Analysis marks in the 9-mark question about financial data and stakeholders, you MUST name specific stakeholders (e.g. employees, suppliers, banks, the local community). Vague references to ''stakeholders'' do not earn marks.</p>", "question": "What must students do to gain Application and Analysis marks about stakeholders?", "options": ["Refer only to shareholders, since stakeholders are never creditable at all here", "Use only the general word ''stakeholders'' throughout the entire answer", "Name specific stakeholders, such as employees, suppliers, banks or the community", "Avoid naming any stakeholder group at all in the final answer given"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains you must name specific stakeholders like employees, suppliers or banks — vague references to ''stakeholders'' do not earn marks."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:9e3752e6', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> Students think profit and cash flow are the same thing — they use the terms interchangeably.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> Profit is total revenue minus total costs over a period. Cash flow is the actual movement of money in and out of the business. A business can be profitable but still have a cash flow problem if customers have not yet paid their invoices.</p>", "question": "Are profit and cash flow the same thing that can be used interchangeably?", "options": ["Yes — profit and cash flow are simply two names for the same figure", "No — but only because cash flow is always higher than profit", "No — a business can be profitable but still have a cash flow problem", "Yes — but only if the business has already paid all of its invoices"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card explains profit is revenue minus costs over a period, while cash flow is the actual movement of money — a business can be profitable yet still face a cash shortage."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:misc:84ed6de8', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'misc', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Misconception check", "reading": "<p><strong>❌ Common misconception:</strong> When asked how a marketing decision affects operations, students write about marketing activities (e.g. ''they will advertise more'') rather than the impact on the operations/production function.</p><p><strong>✅ The correct idea:</strong> The examiner''s report noted this was very common. Once you have identified the marketing activity (for the Understanding mark), you MUST explain the consequence for the operations function specifically — e.g. ''this means operations will need to INCREASE PRODUCTION to meet higher demand.''</p>", "question": "When asked how a marketing decision affects operations, what must the answer explain?", "options": ["The consequence for the operations function specifically, such as increased production", "A definition of operations with no link at all to the marketing decision", "The consequence for the finance function instead of the operations function itself", "Only the marketing activities themselves, such as advertising more heavily"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card explains you must explain the consequence for operations specifically — e.g. ''operations will need to increase production to meet higher demand.''"}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tips:cd020261', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Analyse — 3 marks — The Locked Gate: Understanding Opens Everything", "reading": "\n              <p>Every 3-mark Analyse question in this topic works the same way. There is a <strong>locked gate</strong> — you cannot earn any marks without first showing <strong>Understanding (U)</strong> of the key term in the question.</p>\n              <p><strong>The 3-step formula:</strong></p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>Step 1 — Understanding (U):</strong> Explain what the function or concept DOES. Be specific. Name an activity it carries out.</li>\n                <li><strong>Step 2 — Application (APP):</strong> Link your understanding directly to the business in the case study. Use a specific detail from the text.</li>\n                <li><strong>Step 3 — Analysis (AN):</strong> Explain the impact — what happens as a result? This must be a business-facing consequence (e.g. production increases, costs rise, revenue falls).</li>\n              </ul>\n              <p><strong>❌ Bad Answer (0 marks):</strong><br />\n                <em>\"The finance function is important for BP because it manages the company''s finances efficiently.\"</em><br />\n                This is tautological — saying \"finance manages finances\" earns no understanding mark, and no further marks can follow.</p>\n              <p><strong>✅ Good Answer (3 marks):</strong><br />\n                <em>\"The finance function produces cash-flow forecasts and budgets (U) in order to inform BP''s managers how much money is available for investment into new technologies (APP), such as the wind farms being developed in America, meaning BP can make financially sound decisions to meet its sustainability objectives (AN).\"</em></p>\n              <p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning:</strong> On the real exam, two thirds of candidates scored zero on Q2 (Unilever, 3 marks) and the majority scored zero on Q4 (BP, 3 marks). The reason was identical in both cases: they failed to identify a specific activity of the named function. \"Marketing the product\" or \"managing the business efficiently\" are too vague and score nothing.</p>\n              ", "question": "According to this card, what happens if you don''t show Understanding first in a 3-mark analyse question?", "options": ["You automatically earn 2 out of 3 marks for the remaining two steps", "The examiner awards the mark anyway, provided the answer is detailed", "No further marks can follow, since Understanding is a locked gate", "You can still earn full marks through Application and Analysis alone"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card describes Understanding as a ''locked gate'' — without it, no Application or Analysis marks can be awarded, no matter how good the rest of the answer is."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tips:c6f44161', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Evaluate — 9 marks (Synoptic) — The Synoptic 9: Two Topics, One Answer", "reading": "\n              <p>The final 9-mark question always links <strong>two topics</strong>: one from Component 01 and one from Component 02. There are <strong>9 marks split across 5 skills</strong>: K (1) + U (1) + APP (2) + AN (2) + EVAL (3).</p>\n              <p><strong>The 4-paragraph structure:</strong></p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>Paragraph 1 — K &amp; U:</strong> Define the ''change'' topic (K) and explain how it works (U). Keep this brief — it''s only 2 marks total.<br />\n                  <em>Starter: \"Marketing refers to [K]... This involves activities such as [U]...\"</em></li>\n                <li><strong>Paragraph 2 — APP &amp; AN (Point 1):</strong> Use ONE specific detail from the case study (APP) to explain ONE impact on the named affected area (AN).<br />\n                  <em>Starter: \"In the case of [Business Name], [specific detail from text] (APP)... As a result, this would [impact on the named area — cash flow / costs / revenues] (AN)...\"</em></li>\n                <li><strong>Paragraph 3 — APP &amp; AN (Point 2):</strong> Use a SECOND specific detail from the case study (APP) to explain a SECOND impact on the named affected area (AN).<br />\n                  <em>Starter: \"Furthermore, [second detail from text] (APP)... This means [second impact on the named area] (AN)...\"</em></li>\n                <li><strong>Paragraph 4 — EVAL (3 marks):</strong> Make a clear judgement (1 mark), justify it with context (1 mark), and add a conditional ''it depends on'' statement (1 mark).<br />\n                  <em>Starter: \"Overall, I believe [judgement] (EVAL). This is because [reason using case study context] (EVAL). However, this will ultimately depend on [a contextual condition, e.g. the size of the changes / whether customers continue to buy] (EVAL).\"</em></li>\n              </ul>\n              <p><strong>🚫 Critical Warning — Do NOT write evaluation in the wrong place.</strong> The three evaluation marks are ONLY awarded in the final judgement section. Writing \"I think this is good\" halfway through your analysis does not count as evaluation.</p>\n              <p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning:</strong> Many candidates wrote entirely about ''stakeholders'' without ever naming a specific one (e.g. employees, suppliers, banks). Vague references to ''stakeholders'' earned zero for application AND analysis. You must name them.</p>\n              ", "question": "According to this card, where are the three evaluation marks specifically awarded?", "options": ["Only in the very first paragraph, before any analysis is given", "Automatically, regardless of where in the answer they are written", "Only in the final judgement section, not partway through the analysis", "Anywhere in the answer, as long as a personal opinion is expressed"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card warns evaluation marks are ONLY awarded in the final judgement section — writing ''I think this is good'' halfway through the analysis does not count."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tips:68e6a921', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Analyse — 3 marks (Pairs of linked questions) — Q16 Style: Same Business, Three Different Functions", "reading": "\n              <p>Some questions ask you to analyse the impact of the SAME thing (e.g. being environmentally friendly) on THREE DIFFERENT functions (marketing, HR, finance) in separate 3-mark questions. Each is marked independently using the same U &rarr; APP &rarr; AN structure.</p>\n              <p><strong>Key tip:</strong> Do NOT repeat the same point in each answer. Each response must show a different aspect of the same theme.</p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>Marketing (3 marks):</strong> Focus on how the marketing mix changes — e.g. promotion changes to highlight eco-credentials, or product packaging changes.</li>\n                <li><strong>HR (3 marks):</strong> Focus on how staff are recruited, trained or managed differently — e.g. online interviews to reduce travel, remote working, new IT training.</li>\n                <li><strong>Finance (3 marks):</strong> Focus on costs, cash flow or sources of finance — e.g. higher costs from eco-friendly suppliers, need to monitor cash flow more carefully, may need an increased overdraft.</li>\n              </ul>\n              <p><strong>✅ Good Answer for Finance (3 marks):</strong><br />\n                <em>\"Being environmentally friendly is likely to increase operating costs (U) as NEXT plc. will need to source products from more expensive ethical/eco-friendly suppliers worldwide (APP). This means the finance department may face cash flow difficulties and need to apply for a larger bank overdraft to cover the shortfall (AN).\"</em></p>\n              ", "question": "According to this card, what must you avoid when analysing the same theme across three different functions?", "options": ["Writing three separate three-mark answers instead of one combined answer", "Repeating the same point in each answer instead of a different aspect each time", "Discussing marketing, HR and finance as three genuinely separate business functions", "Using the U to APP to AN structure for each of the three separate answers"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 1, "explain": "The card warns against repeating the same point in each answer — each response must show a different aspect of the same theme, marked independently."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tips:06308eaf', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Recommend — 3 marks — Make a Choice, Back It Up, Compare", "reading": "\n              <p>A 3-mark ''Recommend'' question (like Q16 iv) asks you to make a <strong>clear judgement</strong> about which option is most important or most affected. It is marked on three levels:</p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>1 mark:</strong> A judgement with limited justification — you name a winner but don''t really explain why.</li>\n                <li><strong>2 marks:</strong> A judgement with good justification — you name a winner AND give a clear reason with some reference to relevant information.</li>\n                <li><strong>3 marks:</strong> A judgement with strong, detailed justification — you name a winner AND give a detailed, specific reason that shows clear appraisal of why this function is most affected compared to others.</li>\n              </ul>\n              <p><strong>✅ Good Answer (3 marks):</strong><br />\n                <em>\"The human resources function would be most affected by NEXT plc. being environmentally friendly (JUDGEMENT) because it would impact the way ALL of its workers are employed, trained and managed on a day-to-day basis (JUSTIFICATION). For example, NEXT would need to introduce new IT-based processes, mobile technologies and online training packages to reduce its carbon footprint across its entire workforce (STRONG CONTEXTUAL DETAIL).\"</em></p>\n              ", "question": "According to this card, what separates a 3-mark recommend answer from a 1-mark answer?", "options": ["Writing a much longer answer overall, regardless of its actual content", "Avoiding any reference at all to the specific business that is named in the question", "Simply naming a winner, without giving any reason for the choice made", "Detailed, specific justification showing clear appraisal, not just a named winner"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 3, "explain": "The card explains a 3-mark answer needs detailed, specific justification showing clear appraisal, while a 1-mark answer just names a winner with limited justification."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tips:d61e9121', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "State / Identify — 1–2 marks — Precision Over Paragraphs", "reading": "\n              <p>For 1-mark ''State'' or ''Identify'' questions, one precise point earns the full mark. Do NOT write paragraphs — it wastes time and the examiner is only looking for a single correct statement.</p>\n              <p><strong>The Formula:</strong></p>\n              <ul>\n                <li>One clear, specific, relevant point = 1 mark ✅</li>\n                <li>A vague, general statement = 0 marks ❌</li>\n              </ul>\n              <p><strong>❌ Bad Answer (0 marks) for \"Identify two variable costs\":</strong><br />\n                <em>\"Production costs and salaries.\"</em><br />\n                \"Salaries\" are a <strong>fixed</strong> cost, not variable. \"Production costs\" is too vague.</p>\n              <p><strong>✅ Good Answer (2 marks):</strong><br />\n                <em>\"1. Raw materials / cost of sales. 2. Packaging.\"</em></p>\n              <p><strong>⚠️ Examiner Warning on Variable Costs:</strong> Do NOT accept ''salaries'' — these are fixed costs. The mark scheme specifically excludes this. Only accept wages (which can vary with hours worked), raw materials, packaging and stock/components.</p>\n              ", "question": "According to this card, why would ''salaries'' be rejected as an answer to ''identify a variable cost''?", "options": ["Salaries are not a real business cost recognised in this exam specification", "Salaries only ever apply to businesses with more than one employee", "Salaries are a fixed cost, not a variable one, according to the mark scheme", "Salaries are classed as a form of revenue, not a cost, in this topic"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 2, "explain": "The card''s examiner warning states salaries are a fixed cost — the mark scheme specifically excludes them from being accepted as a variable cost."}'::jsonb),
('business:7-1-final:tips:5b5f012c', 'business', 'business:7-1-final', '7.1 Interdependent Nature of Business', 'tips', 'mcq', 1, '{"readingTitle": "Calculate — 3 marks — Show Your Workings Every Time", "reading": "\n              <p>For calculation questions, you must <strong>always show your workings</strong> — even if you get the final answer wrong, you can still earn marks for correct method.</p>\n              <p><strong>Net Profit Calculation (3 marks) — The Two-Step Method:</strong></p>\n              <ul>\n                <li><strong>Step 1 — Calculate Gross Profit (1 mark):</strong> Revenue &minus; Cost of Sales</li>\n                <li><strong>Step 2 — Calculate Net Profit (2 marks):</strong> Gross Profit &minus; All Other Expenses (Salaries + Rent + Other expenses)</li>\n              </ul>\n              <p><strong>Example (RCP Question):</strong></p>\n              <ul>\n                <li>Gross Profit = £2,000,000 &minus; £500,000 = <strong>£1,500,000</strong> (1 mark)</li>\n                <li>Total Expenses = £1,300,000 + £100,000 + £50,000 = £1,450,000</li>\n                <li>Net Profit = £1,500,000 &minus; £1,450,000 = <strong>£50,000</strong> (2 marks)</li>\n              </ul>\n              <p><strong>Net Profit Margin</strong> = (£50,000 &divide; £2,000,000) &times; 100 = <strong>2.5%</strong></p>\n              <p><strong>⚠️ Warning:</strong> If you only write the final answer with no workings and it is wrong, you score zero. With workings shown, even a mathematical error in the final step earns 2 out of 3 marks.</p>\n              ", "question": "According to this card, what happens if you write only the final answer with no workings and it is wrong?", "options": ["You score zero, since there is no method shown to award partial credit", "You still score full marks, since only the final answer is ever checked", "You automatically score 2 out of 3 marks regardless of the final answer", "The examiner estimates your workings and awards marks accordingly"]}'::jsonb, '{"answer": 0, "explain": "The card warns that with no workings shown, a wrong final answer scores zero — but with workings shown, even a mathematical error can earn 2 out of 3 marks."}'::jsonb),
